02:21.591 --> 02:26.392
The first time I ever saw a movie
at the Cinémathèque Française, I thought:

02:26.462 --> 02:31.923
"Only the French. Only the French
would house a cinema inside a palace".

02:42.612 --> 02:45.911
<i>The movie was Sam Fuller's
Shock Corridor.</i>

02:45.982 --> 02:51.147
Its images were so powerful,
it was like being hypnotized.

02:52.388 --> 02:58.327
I was 20 years old. It was the late '60s, and
I'd come to Paris for a year to study French.

02:58.394 --> 03:01.693
But it was here that I got my real education.

03:02.699 --> 03:07.033
I became a member of what in those days
was kind of a Freemasonry -

03:07.103 --> 03:09.594
the Freemasonry of cinephiles.

03:09.672 --> 03:12.368
What we'd call "film buffs".

03:19.215 --> 03:25.211
I was one of the insatiables. The ones you'd
always find sitting closest to the screen.

03:26.489 --> 03:29.253
Why did we sit so close?

03:29.325 --> 03:32.783
Maybe it was because
we wanted to receive the images first,

03:32.862 --> 03:36.059
when they were still new, still fresh.

03:36.132 --> 03:39.431
Before they cleared
the hurdles of the rows behind us.

03:39.502 --> 03:44.235
Before they had been relayed back
from row to row, spectator to spectator,

03:44.307 --> 03:49.870
until, worn out, the size of a postage stamp,
they returned to the projectionist's cabin.

03:53.182 --> 03:56.583
Maybe, too, the screen really was a screen.

03:56.653 --> 03:59.383
It screened us from the world.

04:10.767 --> 04:15.204
But there was one evening,
in the spring of 1968,

04:15.271 --> 04:19.036
when the world
finally burst through the screen.

04:19.108 --> 04:22.839
The pawn of an obscure coalition
of dubious interests,

04:22.912 --> 04:25.107
the Minister Malraux has driven

04:25.181 --> 04:28.981
Henri Langlois
out of the Cinémathèque Française.

04:29.052 --> 04:32.021
It offered us all
a free and fair conception

04:32.088 --> 04:34.181
of film culture.

04:34.257 --> 04:37.954
Now, for bureaucratic reasons,
culture's arch enemies

04:38.027 --> 04:40.552
have seized this bastion of liberty.

04:42.131 --> 04:43.530
Resist them!

04:43.599 --> 04:46.534
- Liberty isn't given!
- It's taken!

04:46.602 --> 04:48.035
All who love film...

04:48.104 --> 04:49.969
- in France...
- and abroad...

04:50.039 --> 04:51.028
<i>...are with you.</i>

04:51.107 --> 04:53.905
And with Henri Langlois!

05:03.252 --> 05:06.449
It was Henri Langlois
who created the Cinémathèque,

05:06.522 --> 05:11.425
because he liked to show movies instead of
letting them rot in some underground vault.

05:11.494 --> 05:14.554
He'd show any movies - good, bad, old, new.

05:14.630 --> 05:17.394
Silents, Westerns, thrillers.

05:17.467 --> 05:22.461
And all the New Wave filmmakers
came here to learn their craft.

05:22.538 --> 05:25.598
This is where modern cinema was born.

05:25.675 --> 05:27.939
What lies behind it:

05:28.011 --> 05:30.275
The police!

05:31.714 --> 05:34.148
Langlois had been sacked
by the government,

05:34.217 --> 05:38.813
and it seemed like every film buff
in Paris had turned out in protest.

05:38.888 --> 05:41.413
It was our very own cultural revolution.

06:06.516 --> 06:08.507
Excuse me.

06:11.120 --> 06:13.281
Can you remove this?

06:13.356 --> 06:15.483
It's stuck to my lips.

06:16.192 --> 06:19.491
Can you remove my cigarette? It's stuck.

06:19.562 --> 06:21.757
Yes, yes...

06:21.831 --> 06:23.355
Of course.

06:25.001 --> 06:26.935
Sorry.

06:27.937 --> 06:30.929
- What are you? English?
- No, I'm American.

06:31.007 --> 06:33.498
You can put it out now.

06:36.913 --> 06:39.381
- What's your name?
- Matthew.

06:39.449 --> 06:42.418
You're here a lot.
But you never talk to anyone.

06:42.485 --> 06:44.885
We've been wondering
why you're always alone.

06:44.954 --> 06:47.479
I don't really know anybody.

06:48.491 --> 06:53.952
- How come you're chained to the gates?
- I'm not chained to the gates.

06:56.265 --> 06:58.995
- You're awfully clean.
- What?

06:59.068 --> 07:01.628
For someone who likes the cinema so much.

07:01.704 --> 07:03.763
- Do you know Jacques?
- Jacques?

07:03.840 --> 07:06.968
If shit could shit,
it would smell just like Jacques.

07:07.043 --> 07:11.139
My brother's gone to talk to him. When
he gets back, you'll smell Jacques on him.

07:11.214 --> 07:13.842
It's like being around pigs.

07:14.984 --> 07:17.350
- You speak English really well.
- What?

07:17.420 --> 07:21.447
- You speak English really well.
- My mother's English.

07:21.524 --> 07:25.620
- Here's Theo. When I introduce you, sniff.
- Come on.

07:25.695 --> 07:28.220
Truffaut, Godard, Chabrol, Rivette,

07:28.297 --> 07:31.789
and Renoir, Jean Rouch,
Rohmer are here.

07:31.868 --> 07:34.666
Signoret, Jean Marais
and God knows who else.

07:34.737 --> 07:35.965
Marcel Carné too.

07:36.038 --> 07:37.733
Why is Carné here?

07:37.807 --> 07:41.174
What should we do?
Stay or leave?

07:41.244 --> 07:43.542
I don't know.

07:43.613 --> 07:44.875
Theo.

07:44.947 --> 07:47.438
This is Matthew.

07:47.517 --> 07:50.042
- You were right - he's American.
- Hi.

07:52.989 --> 07:56.823
I've seen you around. You've been
coming to all the Nicholas Rays.

07:56.893 --> 07:59.384
Yeah. I really like his movies.

07:59.462 --> 08:02.056
<i>What? They Live by Night?</i>

08:02.131 --> 08:07.501
<i>More like Johnny Guitar
and Rebel Without a Cause.</i>

08:07.570 --> 08:10.937
- You know what Godard wrote about him?
- No, what?

08:11.007 --> 08:13.271
"Nicholas Ray is cinema".

08:14.310 --> 08:16.335
- What's up with you?
- Me?

08:16.412 --> 08:18.710
Come on, stick with me!

08:51.447 --> 08:52.778
Fascists!

08:52.848 --> 08:55.316
- Bastards!
- Assholes!

08:58.988 --> 09:03.220
And that was how I first met
Theo and Isabelle.

09:11.567 --> 09:14.195
I could hear my heart pounding.

09:14.270 --> 09:17.569
I don't know if it was because
I'd just been chased by the police

09:17.640 --> 09:20.871
or because I was already in love
with my new friends.

09:20.943 --> 09:26.848
As we walked and talked, and talked,
and talked - about politics, about movies,

09:26.916 --> 09:29.942
and why the French could never
produce a good rock band...

09:30.019 --> 09:32.886
- I'm starving.
- I forgot the sandwiches.

09:32.955 --> 09:35.856
<i>...I didn't want that night ever to end.</i>

09:39.695 --> 09:44.894
- Didn't you bring anything?
- No, I'm OK. Please, eat. Don't mind me.

09:46.402 --> 09:49.735
- No, I'm really not hungry.
- I've broken it now. Take it.

09:49.805 --> 09:53.332
- You're very kind, but I don't...
- Take it when you're offered it.

09:53.409 --> 09:55.070
Thank you.

09:55.144 --> 09:56.543
- Theo.
- What?

09:56.612 --> 09:59.240
- Don't you have something for Matthew?
- This is fine.

09:59.315 --> 10:02.409
- I gave him a third of mine.
- OK.

10:04.954 --> 10:08.117
I really... I didn't come here
to eat your sandwiches.

10:08.190 --> 10:10.988
- He doesn't want it.
- Yes, he does.

10:11.060 --> 10:15.053
- He's too polite to say he does, aren't you?
- You're both very kind.

10:15.131 --> 10:17.827
So, where are you from exactly?

10:17.900 --> 10:19.800
San Diego.

10:19.869 --> 10:23.805
What about you two?
Were you both born in Paris?

10:23.873 --> 10:28.401
I entered this world
on the Champs Elysées. 1959.

10:28.477 --> 10:30.672
The pavement
of the Champs Elysées.

10:30.746 --> 10:33.681
And you know
what my very first words were?

10:33.749 --> 10:37.879
- No. What?
- "New York Herald Tribune".

10:45.795 --> 10:48.628
Will you come to Rome with me?

10:52.935 --> 10:55.096
Here. Right here. Here.

10:55.171 --> 10:57.696
No, there!

10:57.773 --> 11:01.231
- Good night, Matthew.
- Night.

11:49.992 --> 11:52.085
Dear Mom,

11:52.528 --> 11:55.019
I got some real news this time.

11:56.632 --> 12:00.159
I've just met my first French friends.

12:44.346 --> 12:45.813
Hello?

12:45.881 --> 12:49.317
- Matthew?
- Who is this?

12:49.385 --> 12:52.548
- Don't be so suspicious. It's me.
- Theo?

12:52.621 --> 12:57.058
- Don't tell me I woke you up.
- No, I've been up for ages.

12:57.126 --> 12:59.424
You don't sound as if
you've been up for ages.

12:59.495 --> 13:01.622
I always sound like this in the morning.

13:01.697 --> 13:04.860
Sorry, I have to call you early
because I've got a class at nine.

13:04.934 --> 13:09.633
- Right.
- You want to have dinner tomorrow night?

13:13.309 --> 13:16.710
You mean like a real dinner
in a nice restaurant?

13:16.779 --> 13:19.942
No, no. Not in a restaurant. Here. At home.

13:20.716 --> 13:23.207
Yeah. Sure, that would be great.

13:23.285 --> 13:27.619
- Yes? OK. Why don't you...
- Please get off the phone. It's nine o'clock.

13:27.690 --> 13:31.786
Yes, yes. Why don't you meet us
for a drink first? At the Respite.

13:31.861 --> 13:35.058
Six o'clock. You know where it is?

13:35.130 --> 13:38.031
- Boulevard Saint-Germain?
- Be there at six.

13:46.842 --> 13:49.572
Third floor!

13:49.645 --> 13:52.011
You know, there's room in here for all of us.

13:52.081 --> 13:54.242
Theo and I are contagious.

13:55.217 --> 13:58.778
- We are very contagious.
- Contagious?

13:58.854 --> 14:01.254
You mustn't catch us.

14:19.141 --> 14:21.939
- It's beautiful.
- You think so?

14:22.011 --> 14:24.002
Good luck.

14:32.187 --> 14:34.178
Evening, mother.

14:35.958 --> 14:37.755
What are you doing here?

14:37.826 --> 14:39.726
- We're here for dinner.
- What?

14:39.795 --> 14:41.763
With Matthew.

14:41.830 --> 14:44.355
- Didn't Isabelle say?
- Which Matthew?

14:44.433 --> 14:47.561
This Matthew. He's our new friend.

14:47.636 --> 14:50.469
- Matthew, this is my mother.
- Hi.

14:50.539 --> 14:53.872
- Very pleased to meet you, Matthew.
- Likewise.

14:53.943 --> 14:57.879
- You're American, are you?
- Yeah, I'm from California.

14:57.947 --> 15:03.977
Matthew lives in a nasty student hotel.
Rue Malebranche. So we invited him to dinner.

15:04.053 --> 15:05.020
What's wrong?

15:05.087 --> 15:08.420
What can I say, Isabelle?
I'm cooking for two

15:08.490 --> 15:10.151
and now there are five of us.

15:10.225 --> 15:11.453
Didn't Theo tell you?

15:11.527 --> 15:14.155
No, he didn't. And neither did you.

15:14.229 --> 15:17.323
Have you got mashed potatoes
for brains or what?

15:17.399 --> 15:21.165
- You were supposed to tell her!
- You're crazy!

15:21.236 --> 15:23.500
Bitch, cow, slut...

15:23.572 --> 15:26.735
For God's sake, put a sock in it, you two.

15:29.078 --> 15:32.047
I must apologize
for my children's behavior, Matthew.

15:32.114 --> 15:35.447
No, I'm the one who should be apologizing.

15:35.517 --> 15:37.951
Please, don't put yourself out
on account of me.

15:38.020 --> 15:40.750
That's sweet of you.
You're completely blameless.

15:44.193 --> 15:46.388
Let me look at you.

15:47.129 --> 15:50.895
OK. I want you to make
a good impression on Papa.

16:02.211 --> 16:03.769
Papa, it's me.

16:03.846 --> 16:05.746
We're eating in.

16:05.814 --> 16:07.475
And the Cinémathèque?

16:07.549 --> 16:09.813
Closed until further notice.

16:09.885 --> 16:11.216
Papa!

16:11.286 --> 16:13.447
Can't you see we have a guest?

16:13.522 --> 16:15.786
This is Matthew.

16:17.092 --> 16:19.117
- Sir.
- Matthew.

16:19.194 --> 16:22.163
Matthew's dining with us tonight.

16:22.431 --> 16:26.561
My young Matthew, inspiration is like a baby.

16:26.635 --> 16:30.765
It does not choose a nice,
seemly hour to enter the world.

16:31.273 --> 16:35.209
It has no consideration for the poor poet.

16:36.578 --> 16:39.012
But when it does come,

16:39.081 --> 16:42.710
when it deigns to come,
then you know it's...

16:48.323 --> 16:53.124
Young man. I was speaking to you.
I imagined you were listening.

16:53.195 --> 16:55.527
I was. I'm sorry.

16:57.166 --> 16:58.827
What?

16:59.835 --> 17:02.633
Nothing. I was... I was just...

17:04.506 --> 17:09.808
You seem to be mesmerized
by this tin lighter. I'd like to know why.

17:12.114 --> 17:14.674
- Well?
- George, please. Matthew's our guest.

17:14.750 --> 17:19.346
No, I'm genuinely curious.
I'd like to know why.

17:22.790 --> 17:27.160
I was just... I was fidgeting
with Isabelle's lighter.

17:27.229 --> 17:30.255
I wasn't realizing it,
and I noticed and thought it was rude

17:30.332 --> 17:32.664
so I put it down on the table.

17:32.735 --> 17:37.570
But I put it diagonally across
one of these squares, do you see?

17:37.639 --> 17:39.630
Look.

17:39.708 --> 17:45.578
I noticed that the lighter's length is exactly
the same length as the diagonal itself.

17:45.647 --> 17:47.911
So I put it lengthwise.

17:48.917 --> 17:51.977
Along the outside edge. Look.

17:52.054 --> 17:54.352
- It fits there too.
- Yeah.

17:55.457 --> 17:58.119
But it fits there.

17:58.794 --> 18:02.195
And it fits like this. And like this.

18:02.898 --> 18:05.526
And this way, too.

18:05.601 --> 18:08.900
I bet you if I just split it in half,

18:09.738 --> 18:11.865
it's gotta fit somewhere.

18:12.908 --> 18:16.639
I mean, it really fits anywhere. Look.

18:16.712 --> 18:18.509
You see?

18:18.580 --> 18:22.141
I was noticing that
the more you look at everything -

18:22.217 --> 18:25.618
this table, the objects on it, the refrigerator,

18:25.687 --> 18:27.780
this room, your nose,

18:27.856 --> 18:30.222
the world -

18:30.292 --> 18:34.524
suddenly, you realize that

18:34.596 --> 18:37.827
there's some sort of cosmic harmony

18:37.900 --> 18:40.494
of shapes and sizes.

18:43.005 --> 18:45.235
I was just wondering why.

18:45.307 --> 18:47.571
I don't know why that is.

18:47.643 --> 18:50.111
I know that it is.

18:56.852 --> 18:59.514
You have an interesting friend here.

18:59.588 --> 19:03.024
More interesting, I suspect, than you know.

19:05.460 --> 19:10.124
I mean, when we look around us,
what is it we see?

19:12.134 --> 19:15.001
Complete chaos.

19:15.070 --> 19:17.265
Yet, viewed from above -

19:17.339 --> 19:20.672
viewed, as it were, by God -

19:20.742 --> 19:23.609
everything suddenly fits together.

19:26.215 --> 19:32.916
My children believe that their demonstrations
and sit-ins and happenings...

19:33.956 --> 19:39.258
Well, they believe that these possess
the capacity not only to provoke society,

19:39.328 --> 19:41.819
but also to transform it.

19:46.969 --> 19:51.702
What is it you are saying? If Langlois
is dismissed we shouldn't do anything?

19:51.773 --> 19:56.540
If immigrants are deported, if students
are beaten up, we shouldn't do anything?

19:56.612 --> 20:00.810
All I am saying is
that a little lucidity would not go amiss.

20:00.883 --> 20:03.818
So everyone's wrong but you?

20:04.887 --> 20:07.583
In France? In Italy? Germany? America?

20:07.656 --> 20:13.595
Listen to me. Before you can change the
world, you must realize you are part of it.

20:13.662 --> 20:17.098
You cannot stand outside, looking in.

20:17.165 --> 20:20.100
You're the one who stands outside.

20:20.168 --> 20:23.331
You refused to sign a petition
against the Vietnam war.

20:23.405 --> 20:26.670
Poets don't sign petitions, they sign poems.

20:27.409 --> 20:30.435
- A petition is a poem.
- Yes.

20:30.512 --> 20:33.811
And a poem is a petition.
Thank you, but I'm not gaga yet.

20:33.882 --> 20:37.113
I don't need you
to remind me of my own work.

20:37.853 --> 20:39.411
That's right.

20:39.488 --> 20:42.480
A petition is a poem,
a poem is a petition.

20:42.557 --> 20:48.018
- Yes.
- The most famous lines you ever wrote.

20:49.097 --> 20:51.429
Now look at you.

20:53.568 --> 20:56.298
I hope I'll never be like him.

20:57.706 --> 21:03.406
We should say good night, darling.
We've got a long day ahead of us tomorrow.

21:03.478 --> 21:05.036
George.

21:05.113 --> 21:07.513
Yes, sorry. You were saying?

21:07.582 --> 21:09.015
We should get to bed.

21:11.520 --> 21:15.115
You had something to tell
the children, didn't you?

21:15.190 --> 21:16.851
Yes, of course.

21:16.925 --> 21:18.392
I'm sorry.

21:18.460 --> 21:20.792
The checks are on the mantelpiece.

21:20.862 --> 21:24.525
Don't cash them until
you need them, all right?

21:26.101 --> 21:28.661
Good night, everybody.

21:28.737 --> 21:31.535
Good night, papa.
Have a safe journey.

21:31.606 --> 21:33.233
Good night, dear.

21:33.308 --> 21:34.969
Theo.

21:36.278 --> 21:42.148
- A very good night to you, Matthew.
- It was a pleasure meeting you, sir.

21:42.217 --> 21:45.516
- Very nice meeting you.
- You too. Thank you so much for dinner.

21:45.587 --> 21:46.849
My pleasure.

21:46.922 --> 21:52.087
Why don't you spend the night? I'm not sure
I like the sound of Hotel Malebranche.

21:52.160 --> 21:54.151
Good night.

22:20.655 --> 22:25.422
Why haven't you dazzled us with these
philosophical speculations of yours?

22:25.494 --> 22:27.826
I didn't know I was being philosophical.

22:27.896 --> 22:32.492
- Papa was awfully impressed.
- Papa's full of shit.

22:32.567 --> 22:36.867
I think you're lucky.
I wish my parents were that nice.

22:36.938 --> 22:41.068
Other people's parents
are always nicer than our own.

22:41.143 --> 22:46.513
And yet our own grandparents
are always nicer than other people's.

22:48.216 --> 22:51.083
You know, that's true.
That's absolutely true.

22:51.153 --> 22:54.850
I never thought about it before, but it's true.

22:54.923 --> 22:57.153
Matthew, you're sweet.

22:59.261 --> 23:03.459
This is double the length of...

23:06.701 --> 23:09.033
I'm for bed.

23:21.349 --> 23:23.476
Are you staying?

23:24.486 --> 23:26.977
- Are you OK?
- Yeah, I'm OK.

23:28.457 --> 23:30.186
Good night, Matthew.

23:41.336 --> 23:43.998
Everybody's got a father.

23:44.072 --> 23:45.869
Yes.

23:45.941 --> 23:51.538
But the fact that God doesn't exist
doesn't mean he can take his place.

24:36.391 --> 24:37.881
OK?

24:40.462 --> 24:43.124
- Yeah, it's fine.
- Good night.

24:43.198 --> 24:45.325
- Good night.
- See you in the morning.

24:45.400 --> 24:48.267
See you. Thank...

24:48.336 --> 24:50.327
Thank you.

28:02.664 --> 28:04.825
Good morning.

28:07.635 --> 28:09.660
What was that all about?

28:09.738 --> 28:11.865
I was removing the sleep from your eyes.

28:11.940 --> 28:15.103
Theo lets me do his every morning.

28:16.111 --> 28:18.443
It's a strange thing to want to do.

28:18.513 --> 28:20.811
Didn't you enjoy it?

28:21.549 --> 28:24.450
- Was I supposed to?
- Naturally.

28:31.593 --> 28:32.958
Up.

28:33.027 --> 28:37.657
- What are you waiting for?
- Isabelle, I'm not dressed.

29:37.292 --> 29:38.884
What are you doing?

29:38.960 --> 29:44.921
- What are you doing?
- I've been memorizing this room.

29:44.999 --> 29:48.059
In the future, in my memory,

29:48.136 --> 29:52.129
I shall live a great deal in this room.

29:52.207 --> 29:54.107
<i>Queen Christina.</i>

29:54.175 --> 29:58.168
Where Garbo bids farewell to the room
in which she spent the night with Gilbert.

29:58.246 --> 30:00.976
Bravo!

30:01.049 --> 30:05.247
We have a private wing to ourselves.
The bathroom's at the end of the corridor.

30:05.320 --> 30:10.314
If you aren't there in one minute,
we're coming back to get you.

30:40.822 --> 30:42.813
Come in.

30:44.859 --> 30:47.020
Good morning.

30:47.095 --> 30:49.586
Are you going to church?

30:53.067 --> 30:56.434
Oh, sorry. You want to use my toothbrush?

30:56.504 --> 30:58.301
- No.
- Sure?

30:58.373 --> 31:00.705
I'll use my finger.

31:06.948 --> 31:09.815
- Sleep well?
- Yeah.

31:09.884 --> 31:12.216
I mean, fine.

31:22.497 --> 31:28.265
You know, Matthew, you really do
have the most beautiful pair of lips.

31:30.038 --> 31:32.632
Can I touch them?

31:33.641 --> 31:37.202
You wanna touch my lips?

31:37.278 --> 31:39.337
